yes

Great 👍 Let’s look at a complete SPI byte transfer so you clearly understand how MOSI, MISO, SCLK, and SS work together in the Serial Peripheral Interface protocol.
1️⃣ SPI Signals

SPI uses 4 main lines:
Signal	Meaning
MOSI	Master Out Slave In
MISO	Master In Slave Out
SCLK	Serial Clock (generated by master)
SS / CS	Slave Select (active LOW)

Roles:

    Master generates clock

    Master → Slave data through MOSI

    Slave → Master data through MISO

2️⃣ Example: 1 Byte Transfer

Suppose:

Master sends:

10110011

Slave sends:

01101001

Transfer happens bit by bit simultaneously.
3️⃣ Timing Diagram (Mode 0 example)

Mode 0 → CPOL=0, CPHA=0

    Clock idle LOW

    Data sampled on rising edge

SS    ─────────\____________________/────────

SCLK  ______/‾\_/‾\_/‾\_/‾\_/‾\_/‾\_/‾\_/‾\____
           ↑   ↑   ↑   ↑   ↑   ↑   ↑   ↑
         sample points

MOSI   --1---0---1---1---0---0---1---1--

MISO   --0---1---1---0---1---0---0---1--

Each clock cycle transfers 1 bit.

After 8 clock cycles → 1 byte transferred.
4️⃣ What happens step-by-step
Step 1 – Slave select

Master pulls SS LOW.

SS = 0

This activates the slave device.
Step 2 – Clock starts

Master generates 8 clock pulses.

SCLK:  ↑ ↑ ↑ ↑ ↑ ↑ ↑ ↑

Step 3 – Data shifting

At each clock cycle:
Clock	MOSI (Master→Slave)	MISO (Slave→Master)
1	1	0
2	0	1
3	1	1
4	1	0
5	0	1
6	0	0
7	1	0
8	1	1

So both devices exchange a byte at the same time.

This is called:

Full-duplex communication

5️⃣ Internal shift registers

SPI hardware uses shift registers.

Master register:

10110011 → shifted out via MOSI

Slave register:

01101001 → shifted out via MISO

Each clock:

Master shift → MOSI
Slave shift  → MISO

And each receives bits simultaneously.
6️⃣ End of transmission

After 8 bits:

SS → HIGH

Communication stops.
7️⃣ Real embedded example

Suppose a microcontroller reads a register from a sensor.

Sequence:

1. SS = LOW
2. Send command byte
3. Send address
4. Slave sends data
5. SS = HIGH

Common SPI devices:

    Flash memory

    ADC/DAC

    Displays

    Sensors

8️⃣ Key characteristics of SPI

✔ Full duplex
✔ Very fast (MHz range)
✔ Simple hardware
✔ No addressing (uses chip select)

But:

❌ Needs more wires than I²C.

✅ One important concept many students miss:

Even when the master only wants to receive data, it must still send dummy data (like 0xFF) to generate clock pulses.

If you want, I can also explain why SPI is much faster than I²C and Universal Asynchronous Receiver/Transmitter (UART) — this is a very common embedded systems interview question.

before explaining why spi is faster than i2fc and uart , tell me the difference between data sample and data shift and what happens exactly while transferring and receiving one byte at same time using spi in the above example, in which edge of each clock pulse , the data is stable or shifting and when the slave is reading as welln as master?

Good question — understanding data shift vs data sample is the key to understanding SPI timing.

We’ll use SPI Mode-0 (CPOL=0, CPHA=0) as in the previous example of Serial Peripheral Interface.
1️⃣ Difference Between Data Shift and Data Sample
Data Shift

Shifting means the device moves the next bit from its shift register to the output line (MOSI or MISO).

Example shift register:

Master register: 10110011

Each clock cycle:

Before shift: 10110011
After shift : 0110011X

So next bit appears on MOSI.

👉 In short:

Data shift = placing next bit on the line

Data Sample

Sampling means the receiving device reads the logic level present on the line.

Example:

MOSI line = 1
Slave reads → stores '1'

👉 In short:

Data sample = reading the bit from the line

2️⃣ Rule in SPI

SPI separates shift edge and sample edge so data is stable when read.

For Mode-0:
Clock Edge	Operation
Falling edge	Data shift
Rising edge	Data sample

This ensures data is stable before sampling.
3️⃣ Timing Diagram (Mode-0)

Clock      ___/‾‾‾\___/‾‾‾\___/‾‾‾\___

Edge         ↑     ↓     ↑     ↓

Operation   Sample Shift Sample Shift

So:

    Falling edge → next bit placed

    Rising edge → bit is read

4️⃣ Example: Master and Slave exchange 1 byte

Master sends:

10110011

Slave sends:

01101001

Both have shift registers.
5️⃣ Step-by-Step (first few clocks)
Before first clock

Both devices place first bit on the bus.

MOSI = 1
MISO = 0

Data lines are stable.
Clock 1 Rising Edge (Sample)

Master samples MISO
Slave samples MOSI

Master reads → 0
Slave reads → 1

Clock 1 Falling Edge (Shift)

Both devices shift registers.

Next bits appear:

MOSI = 0
MISO = 1

Clock 2 Rising Edge (Sample)

Master reads → 1
Slave reads → 0

Clock 2 Falling Edge (Shift)

Next bits appear.

MOSI = 1
MISO = 1

This repeats for 8 clock cycles.
6️⃣ Complete table
Clock	Rising Edge (Sample)	Falling Edge (Shift)
Start	First bit already present	
1	Master reads MISO, Slave reads MOSI	Next bit shifted
2	Read next bit	Next bit shifted
3	Read next bit	Next bit shifted
4	Read next bit	Next bit shifted
5	Read next bit	Next bit shifted
6	Read next bit	Next bit shifted
7	Read next bit	Next bit shifted
8	Read last bit	End
7️⃣ What “data stable” means

During sampling edge, the signal must not change.

Example:

Clock:    ___/‾‾‾\___
            ↑

MOSI:   ----1---------

At that ↑ edge, the bit must already be stable.
8️⃣ Why SPI uses two edges

If shifting and sampling happened at the same moment:

data changing while reading

→ Wrong bit may be captured.

So SPI ensures:

Shift edge  → change data
Sample edge → read data

9️⃣ Why master and slave read simultaneously

SPI is full-duplex.

Both have shift registers:

Master shift register
Slave shift register

Every clock:

Master shift → MOSI
Slave shift  → MISO
Master sample ← MISO
Slave sample  ← MOSI

So transmit and receive happen at the same time.

✅ Simple summary
Operation	Meaning
Shift	Put next bit on MOSI/MISO
Sample	Read bit from MOSI/MISO
Stable data	Data must not change while sampling

For Mode-0:

Falling edge → shift
Rising edge → sample

If you'd like, I can also show a very clear register-level diagram of SPI hardware inside a microcontroller (shift register + clock + buffer) — it makes the simultaneous TX/RX behavior crystal clear for interviews and debugging.

now explain why this is fatser than i2c and uart

Let’s compare why the Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI) protocol is generally faster than I²C and Universal Asynchronous Receiver/Transmitter (UART).

The difference comes from clocking method, protocol overhead, and data direction.
1️⃣ Clocking Method
SPI – Dedicated Clock

SPI uses a separate clock line (SCLK) generated by the master.

    Every clock pulse transfers 1 bit

    Data transfer is tightly synchronized

Example:

Clock pulses: 8
Bits transferred: 8

So 1 clock = 1 bit transfer.

SPI clocks can easily reach:

10 MHz – 50 MHz (or more depending on hardware)

I²C – Shared Clock with Protocol Control

I²C also has a clock, but it includes extra protocol control.

Standard speeds:
Mode	Speed
Standard	100 kHz
Fast	400 kHz
Fast+	1 MHz
High-speed	3.4 MHz

But every byte requires extra bits:

8 data bits
+ 1 ACK bit

So 9 clock pulses per byte instead of 8.

Also includes:

    Start condition

    Address transmission

    ACK/NACK checking

    Stop condition

These reduce effective speed.
UART – No Clock (Asynchronous)

Universal Asynchronous Receiver/Transmitter does not use a clock line.

Instead, it uses:

    Start bit

    Data bits

    Optional parity

    Stop bit

Typical frame:

1 Start
8 Data
1 Stop

Total:

10 bits for 8 bits of data

So efficiency is only:

8 / 10 = 80%

And speed is limited by baud rate (e.g., 115200 bps).
2️⃣ Protocol Overhead
SPI

Very little overhead.

Typical transfer:

CS LOW
8 clock pulses → 1 byte
CS HIGH

No addressing or acknowledgments.
I²C

Much more overhead.

Example transfer:

START
ADDRESS
ACK
REGISTER
ACK
DATA
ACK
STOP

Many extra clock cycles.
UART

Each byte includes framing bits:

Start + Data + Stop

So extra transmission time.
3️⃣ Full Duplex vs Half Duplex
SPI

SPI is full-duplex.

During each clock cycle:

Master → Slave (MOSI)
Slave → Master (MISO)

So two directions happen simultaneously.
I²C

I²C is half-duplex.

Only one device talks at a time on the SDA line.
UART

UART is technically full-duplex (separate TX/RX), but:

    No shared clock

    Requires timing recovery

So maximum speeds are usually lower.
4️⃣ Hardware Simplicity

SPI hardware is simple:

Shift register + clock

Data shifts every clock edge with minimal control logic.

I²C needs:

    Bus arbitration

    Address decoding

    ACK control

UART needs:

    Baud rate generators

    Start/stop detection

    Timing synchronization

More logic → slower effective throughput.
5️⃣ Speed Comparison

Typical real-world speeds:
Protocol	Speed
SPI	10–50 Mbps
I²C	100 kbps – 3.4 Mbps
UART	9.6 kbps – 1 Mbps (common)

So SPI can be 10–100× faster.
6️⃣ Simple analogy

Think of three communication styles:

SPI:

Private road between two devices
No traffic rules
Very fast

I²C:

Shared road with traffic signals
Devices must take turns

UART:

Mail letters without synchronized timing
Each letter needs envelope (start/stop bits)

✅ Key reasons SPI is faster

    Dedicated clock

    No start/stop overhead per byte

    No addressing phase

    Full-duplex transfer

    Simple hardware shifting

If you want, I can also explain one very important practical concept: why SPI still needs “dummy bytes” when reading data from a slave, which confuses many embedded developers when debugging SPI drivers.

